acteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]},{"name":"FitzWalter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English, Irish: relationship name from Anglo-Norman French  <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (  see  Fitz  ) + the personal name   Walter  , ‘son of  <i>Walter</i>’."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitzwater","meanings":["Irish: altered form of <b>Fitzwalter</b>, a patronymic from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + the personal name   Walter  , meaning ‘son of <i>Walter</i>’.","History: This is the name of a family of Norman origin, descended from Godfrey, Count of Brionne (died <i>c.</i> 1010). Godfrey's grandson, Richard FitzGilbert, accompanied William the Conqueror and was made Lord of Clare. His great-grandson was Robert FitzWalter, one of the barons who guaranteed the Magna Carta in 1215."]},{"name":"Walter","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."]},{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"John FitzWalter de Bratoft II was born about 1260, in Bratoft, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Walter FitzJohn de Bratoft. He had at least 1 daughter. He died about 1318, in his hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"Abt 1260–Abt 1318":"umbes 1260–umbes 1318","1260–1318":"1260–1318","1291–1338":"1291–1338","1233–1287":"1233–1287","1338":"1338","Abt 1260":"umbes 1260","Abt 1287":"umbes 1287","1233":"1233","1287":"1287","1260":"1260","Abt 1318":"umbes 1318","1291":"1291","1318":"1318","Bratoft, Spilsby, East Lindsey, Lincolnshire, England":"Bratoft, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1260–Abt 1318":"noin 1260–noin 1318","1260–1318":"1260–1318","1291–1338":"1291–1338","1233–1287":"1233–1287","1338":"1338","Abt 1260":"noin 1260","Abt 1287":"noin 1287","1233":"1233","1287":"1287","1260":"1260","Abt 1318":"noin 1318","1291":"1291","1318":"1318","Bratoft, Spilsby, East Lindsey, Lincolnshire, England":"Bratoft, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1260–Abt 1318":"environ 1260–environ 1318","1260–1318":"1260–1318","1291–1338":"1291–1338","1233–1287":"1233–1287","1338":"1338","Abt 1260":"environ 1260","Abt 1287":"environ 1287","1233":"1233","1287":"1287","1260":"1260","Abt 1318":"environ 1318","1291":"1291","1318":"1318","Bratoft, Spilsby, East Lindsey, Lincolnshire, England":"Bratoft, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"John FitzWalter de Bratoft II est né environ 1260, à Bratoft, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de Walter FitzJohn de Bratoft. Il a eu au moins 1 fille. Il est décédé environ 1318, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 60 ans."},"de":{"Abt 1260–Abt 1318":"um 1260–um 1318","1260–1318":"1260–1318","1291–1338